article.description: Gaati Werema had 29 points and 16 rebounds to lead Prairie View A&M to a 74-49 victory over Southern on Saturday.
article.headline: Werema's double-double helps Prairie View A&M win SWAC
article.linkText: Prairie View A&M claims SWAC, ticket to dance
article.story:
BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- Gaati Werema wanted to put a happier ending on this Southwestern Athletic Conference tournament.

Werema certainly did that with 29 points and 16 rebounds to lead Prairie View A&M to a 74-49 victory over Southern in the championship game Saturday after tearing a knee ligament in the semifinals a year earlier.

"That's all she's been talking about was coming back and helping us win another championship," said teammate Candice Thomas, who added 18 points. "She came out and did it."

The Lady Panthers (23-10) went on to lose in the championship game last season without Werema, the SWAC player of the year and tournament MVP. They will carry a 19-game winning streak into the NCAA tournament, earning an automatic berth with their second SWAC title game victory in three years.

Werema scored 11 points in a 16-0 run that turned a close game into a rout. Her teammates had given her a pep talk to help make sure memories of her knee injury weren't weighing on her.

"They came to me and were like, 'Just play basketball," she said. "I pushed through it and today I came through."

Southern (16-13) had cut a 14-point deficit down to two by halftime but managed only one field goal in the opening 10 minutes of the second half. The Jaguars scored just 14 points after the break, making 5-of-30 shots.

"Gaati is a great player," Southern coach Sandy Pugh said. "We didn't match her intensity down the stretch. When she picked it up, I thought we got our heads down.

"I think the kids got a little frustrated."

Prairie View coach Cynthia Cooper-Dyke called it the "best half of basketball that we've played this year."

"And this was a heck of a time to do it," she said.

Southern is the last team to beat Prairie View, winning 65-59 on Jan. 5 for the Lady Panthers only conference loss.

Dominique Smith added 15 points and eight assists for Prairie View.

Cooper-Dyke said she told her team at the half to pick it up defensively.

"We defend, we rebound and we run," said the two-time WNBA MVP for the Houston Comets. "When we have those three working together, we feel we are a pretty tough team to beat."

Deidra Jackson led Southern with 19 points.

"We played good for 28 minutes but just gave up for 5 minutes," Jackson said. "We tried to come back strong but it was too late."

Prairie View shot 46 percent from the floor and made 16-of-18 free throws.

Cooper-Dyke said her team isn't satisfied with just getting to the NCAA tournament, but wants to become the first SWAC team to win a game.

"That's our main goal," she said. "We're not finished yet. This is just one goal that we have achieved and we have set some other goals for ourselves."
